  "prompt": "What is the difference between a royalty and a license?",
  "response": "A royalty and a license are related concepts, often used in the context of intellectual property, but they refer to different aspects of a legal and financial relationship.\n\n1. **License:**\n   - A license is a legal agreement or permission granted by a licensor (owner of a product, service, or intellectual property) to a licensee (a person or company seeking to use that product, service, or property).\n   - It specifies the terms under which the licensee can use the intellectual property. This can include scope, duration, geographical area, and exclusivity.\n   - Licenses can be exclusive or non-exclusive and can cover different types of intellectual properties, such as patents, copyrights, trademarks, or software.\n\n2. **Royalty:**\n   - A royalty is a payment made by the licensee to the licensor for the right to use the licensor's property or assets as granted in the license agreement.\n   - It is typically structured as a percentage of revenue generated from the use of the licensed property, a fixed fee per unit sold, or sometimes as a flat regular fee.\n   - Royalties are a way for the licensor to earn revenue from their intellectual property by allowing others to profit from it as well.\n\nIn essence, the license is the contractual framework that allows the use of intellectual property, while a royalty is one of the financial mechanisms through which the licensor is compensated for this use.",
